docs.abstract: The United States and Mexico made progress toward a Nafta agreement during two days of talks in Washington this week, but Canada still needs to be brought to the table.
docs.snippet: The United States and Mexico made progress toward a Nafta agreement during two days of talks in Washington this week, but Canada still needs to be brought to the table.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The United States and Mexico are edging closer to agreement on how to rewrite key portions of the North American Free Trade Agreement, with the two countries making progress on rules related to automobiles and other remaining issues during two days of meetings that ended on Friday in Washington.

headline.main: United States and Mexico Are Nearing Nafta Compromise
headline.print_headline: U.S. and Mexico Near Compromise on Nafta

docs.abstract: The Trump administration cited national security concerns in announcing that it was starting an investigation into imported uranium ore, a key ingredient in America’s nuclear arsenal.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration cited national security concerns in announcing that it was starting an investigation into imported uranium ore, a key ingredient in America’s nuclear arsenal.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration said on Wednesday that it was starting an investigation into uranium imports, potentially opening another front in an expansive trade war that has shaken alliances with countries around the world.

headline.main: U.S. Opens Inquiry Into Uranium Imports in Sign That Trade War Is Spreading
headline.print_headline: U.S. Inquiry Into Uranium Imports May Signal New Front in Trade War

byline.original: By Ana Swanson and Brad Plumer

docs.abstract: President Trump has said that trade wars are “easy to win,” but the question is whether he has a plan to achieve the results he wants.
docs.snippet: President Trump has said that trade wars are “easy to win,” but the question is whether he has a plan to achieve the results he wants.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The United States and China hit each other with punishing tariffs on Friday as the two nations tipped into a long-feared trade war that is only expected to escalate.

headline.main: Trump Starts a Trade War, but the Path to Success Remains Unclear
headline.print_headline: Trade War Rises, and Trump Plan Remains a Puzzle

byline.original: By Ana Swanson and Neil Irwin

docs.abstract: But their offers may not satisfy a president who has shown a willingness to embrace trade tensions to extract more from American trading partners.
docs.snippet: But their offers may not satisfy a president who has shown a willingness to embrace trade tensions to extract more from American trading partners.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — President Trump’s threat to impose tariffs on imported cars is working, sending foreign leaders from Mexico to Japan racing to the negotiating table to make deals. But their offers may not satisfy a president who has shown a willingness to embrace trade tensions in an effort to extract more from American trading partners.

headline.main: Specter of Trump’s Car Tariffs Forces Allies to Give Ground in Talks
headline.print_headline: Threat of Tariff Works, For Now

byline.original: By Jack Ewing, Ana Swanson and Motoko Rich

docs.abstract: China offered American officials the package in trade talks last weekend, but the deal could quickly fizzle as the White House continues with its plans to impose tariffs on the country.
docs.snippet: China offered American officials the package in trade talks last weekend, but the deal could quickly fizzle as the White House continues with its plans to impose tariffs on the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — China offered to purchase nearly $70 billion of energy, agricultural and manufactured products from the United States in the first year of a deal that would require the Trump administration to suspend tariffs on Chinese products, a person familiar with the talks said.

headline.main: China Offers to Buy Nearly $70 Billion of American Goods if U.S. Halts Tariffs
headline.print_headline: China Offers to Buy $70 Billion in Goods if U.S. Halts Tariffs

docs.abstract: Three independent members of the board will have “full power and authority” to evaluate any privatization efforts proposed by Elon Musk, the chief executive.

docs.abstract: John Schnatter had already stepped down as C.E.O. of Papa John’s in December after he criticized the N. F. L’s handling of protests by football players.
docs.snippet: John Schnatter had already stepped down as C.E.O. of Papa John’s in December after he criticized the N. F. L’s handling of protests by football players.
docs.lead_paragraph: John Schnatter, the founder of Papa John’s Pizza, has resigned as chairman of the board of Papa John’s International, the company announced late Wednesday, hours after he apologized for using a racial slur in a comment about black people during a conference call in May.

headline.main: Racial Slur Leads to Papa John’s Founder Quitting Chairman Post
headline.print_headline: Apology and Exit at Papa John’s After a Racial Slur

docs.abstract: The chain’s executive chairman turned the company into a worldwide corporate force, attempting to sell social justice along with coffee.
docs.snippet: The chain’s executive chairman turned the company into a worldwide corporate force, attempting to sell social justice along with coffee.
docs.lead_paragraph: After more than three decades managing Starbucks’s growth from a tiny local chain into a global coffee giant, and wading into touchy political topics along the way, Howard D. Schultz is leaving the company.

headline.main: Howard Schultz at Starbucks: Coffee, Activism and Controversy
